To everyone,<br>
Well, we have finally made it to thread 100.  It has been a long journey from when this site began.  I am grateful to be able to take part in a what really is a &quot;one of a kind site&quot;.  For the big &quot;100&quot; thread, I have a challenge for all of you: vet, protestor, student, family, friends, or concerned citizen.  Since, at the time of this writing, I don't know how long this site will continue, I think there is one thing all of us can participate in and perhaps leave a definite mark for all those who visit here.<br><br>
Bill McCloud, a Vietnam Vet and Junior High School teacher put together a terrific book called &quot;What Should We Tell Our Children About Vietnam?&quot;, in which he posed that question to a host of personalities, leaders, vets and citizens that lived through the Vietnam era.  The book dealt with what each person felt were the lessons learned from that war that should be taught to every child in America.  It is a book worth reading.<br><br>
So, here is my challenge for anyone who visits here,<br><br>
WHAT ARE THE LESSONS LEARNED FROM THE VIETNAM WAR THAT WE SHOULD SHARE WITH OUR CHILDREN AND MAKE SURE THEY LEARN?<br><br>
I would like everyone to share anything they feel is important.  These lessons can be related to combat operations, foreign policy, government, military service, the draft, relations with other countries, social issues, or just personal observations and experiences that you feel to be important.  I don't believe there will be any definite answers, but what we post will be of value to many people who visit here (like me, a student of the Vietnam experience and the son of a vet).  We can perhaps debate and/or discuss some of the issues or ideas posted too.<br>
                             <br><br>
If anyone wants to contact me, I will be happy to share my e-mail address.  I just don't like to post all over the net.<br>
Best wishes to all!!
